Reference-contexts: As the load increases further, reservations may be made via the piggyback channel and hence the number of CMS's required will decrease. The solution to the number of CMS's to allocate is rather simple: allocate all slots that are not being used for data as CMS's <ref> [2] </ref>. At low load very many more CMS's will be allocated than are required. The surplus of CMS's reduces the probability of collision to a very low level which in turn reduces the access delay for the data; every collision adds one round-trip period to the access delay. <p> All the results obtained herein used the algorithm of Rivest as described in [3] and also used in <ref> [2] </ref>. The performance of the p-persistence algorithm is not very sensitive to the exact value of p. Ideally p would equal 1/N a , where N a is the number of users competing for each slot.
